"reviewcomment":"The restaurant Ständige Vertretung (Permanent representation) owes its name to the time when Germany was divided in two, when West Berlin was formally no part of the territory of the Federal Republic of Germany (although its citizens were indeed west germans).<br><br> This explains why its walls are full of decorations of the time: old signals of the train station of Bonn (former capital, located in Rhineland-Westfalia), pictures of politicians of the time of the wirschaftswunder (economic miracle). The Permanent Representation was also the name of the representation office of the Federal Republic of Germany in Berlin; the russians (co-administrators of the city with the other allies) never allowed West Germany to have a higher-ranking representation.<br><br> And Permanent Representation also means: the restaurant presents itself as a representation of the Rhineland gastronomy and they do mean to stay here, which they do deserve. The Ständige Vertretung is probably where you can get the best pork knuckle (eisbein!) with choucroute in town; and if you are a resolute eater, don&#39;t think it twice and order a blood sausage (blutwurst). They are great.<br><br> In spite of their location, next to the Friedrichstrasse train station, and the large amount of tourists (the place is as central as it can be), this is not at all a tourist trap but a restaurant of german (rhineland) cuisine also patronized by so many germans. Most of them berliners.<br><br> Do not miss the real Cologne beer (Kölsch type, here sold under the mark Gaffels), which is hard to find elsewhere in Berlin.<br><br> The flammkuchen (something in between a crêpe and a pizza) are also great.<br><br> Prices are reasonable and the service, although the restaurant is always full, is quite good. The waiters and waitresses do earn their tip.",
