"ogimage":"http://s3-media3.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/n6cMbNgTkGG_5LuqHZ08IQ/l.jpg",
"rating":"3.5",
"reviewcomment":"we were wandering around looking for a place for dinner away from what would for sure be tourist traps on Unter der Linden near Brandenberger Tor. i&#39;m sure we were not walking down the right roads but it seems like few options are available, and yet fewer are open on a Saturday evening.<br><br>trusty ol&#39; yelp led us to Maximilian&#39;s, tucked indoors on the main level of an office building. boy was it popular with the locals! there is a relaxed &#34;patio&#34; seating area and cozy tables and booths inside. service was a bit slow to get the menu, to take our orders, to get the cheque, to bring the bill. not sure if it&#39;s just the more relaxed atmosphere of Europe/Germany that we&#39;re not used to in North America so I won&#39;t hold it against this place.<br><br>- BERLINER EISBEIN MIT KARTOFFELN, SAUERKRAUT UND ERBSPÜREE (13,90€) - little ol&#39; me gets served this dish with Berlin-style pork hock the size of my HEAD with boiled potatoes, sauerkraut, and roasted pea puree. the pork was so flavourful and boiled to the point where the skin/fat/meat was all buttahhh. by the time I was finished, it looked like I had barely touched the plate form the opposite angle. more ridiculous, my leftovers proved enough for 3 tasty tasty sandwiches the following day and a half. wunderbar :)<br>- SCHWEINSHAXE MIT SEMMELKNÖDEL UND SAUERKRAUT (11,90€) - this traditionally Bavarian roasted pork knuckle comes with bread dumpling and sauerkraut. not a fan of bread dumpling, as it&#39;s much too dense for me, but the pork had an insanely crackling skin. so crispy!!<br><br>prices are verrrry decent for the portions! paulaner is a plenty here. this place is solid.",
